<body>
<sec id="summary">
  <title>Summary</title>
  <p>The khmer software is a set of command-line tools built around a
  Python library designed for analysis of large DNA sequence
  collections. Functionality in khmer has primarily been motivated by
  scaling issues with (meta)genome and (meta)transcriptome assembly
  (<xref alt="Crusoe et al., 2015" rid="ref-crusoe2015" ref-type="bibr">Crusoe
  et al., 2015</xref>). khmer provides convenient access to several
  <italic>k</italic>-mer based operations on DNA sequence collections,
  such as abundance filtering, error trimming, assembly graph
  partitioning, and most notably, abundance normalization of reads
  (<xref alt="Brown et al., 2012" rid="ref-brown2012" ref-type="bibr">Brown
  et al., 2012</xref>) and streaming error trimming of reads
  (<xref alt="Q. Zhang et al., 2015" rid="ref-zhang2015" ref-type="bibr">Q.
  Zhang et al., 2015</xref>). All of these operations utilize khmer’s
  implementation of two primary data structures, the Bloom filter and
  the Count-Min Sketch, for efficient probabalistic storage of
  <italic>k</italic>-mer presence or <italic>k</italic>-mer abundance,
  respectively
  (<xref alt="Pell et al., 2012" rid="ref-pell2012" ref-type="bibr">Pell
  et al., 2012</xref>;
  <xref alt="J. A. C.-K. Zhang Qingpeng AND Pell, 2014" rid="ref-zhang2014" ref-type="bibr">J.
  A. C.-K. Zhang Qingpeng AND Pell, 2014</xref>).</p>
  <p>Release version 2.1 of the khmer software includes several new
  features that extend its utility to a wider set of sequence processing
  and analysis problems. These include the following: support for
  variable-coverage trimming of sequence reads; support for
  <italic>k</italic> &gt; 32 using the non-reversible hash function
  MurmurHash3 (https://github.com/aappleby/smhasher); a new optional
  Count-Min Sketch implementation providing increased storage
  efficiency; support for assembly directly from a
  <italic>k</italic>-mer graph; a script for computing a compact de
  Bruijn graph from a <italic>k</italic>-mer graph; and several examples
  of khmer’s Python and C++ APIs for those interested in using and
  extending the library.</p>
</sec>
